metadata.name: Dreamcatcher Forest #257
metadata.description:
"Dreamcatcher Forest" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022. The illustration in this work draws inspiration from Native American dreamcatchers, a protective talisman crafted from beautifully intricate patterns of woven thread, built from natural materials & colorful beads.

Dreamcatchers are used to protect dreamers while they sleep. Good dreams are able to slip through the web to meet the sleeper beneath, while bad dreams are trapped and prevented.

- Use the "S" key to save a PNG image.
- Use the "P" key to export a print-quality image.

metadata.name: aRo #127
metadata.description:
aRo "a Representation of"

Like a ladder or a hammer, art is often a tool. The less practical and most bizarre, basically the most overcomplicated self-made tool anyone could ever imagine. But it's THE tool to explore ideas.
I created this one to investigate, to poke and nudge at a few concepts that seem to go hand-in-hand.
Firstly, Representation, as in changing something to better explain it. Metaphors, symbols, codes —the very fabric of art, religion, and society. And secondly, the aesthetics of recursion or accumulation.

While many generative art projects pick buildings and landscapes as their subject, most artworks are made of particles arranged, connected and stretched to create bigger structures, to become textures or both.

But there's a distinct texture that arises from mobs. And another, somewhat similar, that belongs to the accumulation and hoarding of not-same-objects or shapes.

I can't tell if it's a street grid, a collage, a group of shrines or actual cells, but to scratch all these potential meanings using accumulation, hoarding and mobs, is what brought the texture I was looking for.

What happens when a flower has more petals than pixels? Why do we know there's more layers to that thumbnail?
My best answer is:

--Press "s" key to save a bigger image (2400x3200 px)

metadata.name: Part:Counterpart #236
metadata.description:
'Part:Counterpart' is an experiment in form, disintegration, and context. Each work is created within one of three modes, Part, Counterpart, or Part:Counterpart.

In experimenting, I've enjoyed taking a simple composition and breaking it down with various methods. This transforms the original composition into something new, but it also begins to lose what the original had to say. This isn't necessarily a bad thing, and I want to dive a little deeper and explore ideas as a sort of tangible substance. Already we're comparing ideas against their translations and evolutions, but what happens if we present them both within the context of the other?

Additionally, what if we present both of these ideas with echoes and tangents, discussion around the ideas and their practical applications instead of imagined? Sure, these aren't our idea, or even our translation, but they exist only because the originals do.

How does this change our opinion of the original? Is every idea destined to be picked apart and reimagined forever until it bears only a faint resemblance? Where is the line between our Counterpart and an echo?

This piece hopes to inspire contemplation on the nature of storytelling and artistic inspiration.

10% of ideas are encrypted to obscure the original Part.
Press ’s’ to save a 3600x4500 png.
Press ‘p’ to save the original Part, pure and untouched.

metadata.description:
Social Networks.
Molecular Clouds.
Neuronal Circuitries.
Quantum Mechanical Structures.

Blurring Boundaries.
Infinite Self-Similarities.

Total.
Mess.

Perfect.
Order.

/////
Each element (besides the painting ground textures) is based on the underlying subdivided grid which is sometimes exposed like some kind of preliminary drawing.

Note on the split:
After seeing some of the outputs, Sermin had a dream about “Breeding Grounds” and I decided to incorporate events and feelings from her dream into the project. That's how the names of the color palettes came about. Thank you for naming them, Sermin!

Press 's' to save a .png with the current resolution (2000x3000).
If you want a file with higher resolution and/or without the “Painting Ground Textures” for printing please contact me via Twitter or Discord.

Created with p5.js

Twitter: @serminmin / @pxlshrd

metadata.name: CA Panico #100
metadata.description:
Third chapter of the trilogy dedicated to Stephen Wolfram's cellular automata.
 
Compared to CA Vista and CA Monti, CA Panico aims to further abstract the concept of landscape using CA rules in a more massive way.

The great variety of CA rules that controls the coloring and textures, noise influence, division into quadrants, chance of having glitches and outages all combined with 25 palettes and 5 different formats means that the outputs will be very varied and peculiar.

Press 'S' to download, you can zoom downloaded output to enjoy all the details.

metadata.name: iterations #400
metadata.description:
Multiple drawing methods create a broad range of stippled output. Inverted drawing (black on white, rather than white on black) is a 5% likelihood, and rainbo mode (all colors rather than one color) is a 1% likelihood. Health and happiness to you during this holiday season!

Created in p5.js

metadata.name: Gen DOS Punk #6
metadata.description:
Gen DOS Punks - A Generative Tribute to DOS Punks!

Each Punk is a unique 1/1.

222 fxrand() functions in total to ensure almost no duplicates whatsoever!

Features weren't included due to a technical limitation. However if you want to see those, you can check the console logs - they're all there!

You can also triple-tap on a phone or click S on your keyboard to perform a "right-click save as".

-----

Find me on Twitter @uoisnlli

And find the 'DOS Punks' creator on Twitter @maxcapacity

#DOSLIFE

Not affiliated with DOS Punks or CryptoPunks/Larva Labs

metadata.name: Wiggle #291
metadata.description:
Wiggle is a long-form generative collection of 1024 editions by Geoff Stearns that explores repetition using simple sine waves. There are 15 possible color palettes and the wave amplitude, complexity, and size are all variable.

The color palettes used in Wiggle are the same palettes used in Geoff's previous work, Hash Three Points (https://h3p.deconcept.com) and the projects share the same number of editions to invite collectors to find complimentary sets or pairs across the two projects.

https://twitter.com/tensafefrogs/status/1469491338714492929

metadata.name: Jellyfish #5
metadata.description:
Cognomen fxhash mint #3.

Each token features a jellyfish with a unique scrolling shader pattern and color scheme. The jellyfish are pixelated and dithered, and their pixel size, dithering pattern and color depth varies. The number of tentacles and their size is randomized.

There is a ~2% chance to mint a black and white jellyfish.

Created with Three.js by Mr. Doob.
